{
  "texts": [
    "RGB imaging provides excellent spatial resolution at a low cost, making it widely used in food, postharvest quality assessment, and agricultural applications (Mei et al. 2022).",
    "RGB images offer rich texture and structural information useful for object recognition and scene analysis, but they lack the spectral depth of HSIs.",
    "This spectral depth is crucial for identifying the physical and chemical attributes of food samples like fruits, vegetables, and animal-derived foods.",
    "Therefore, converting readily available RGB images into accurate hyperspectral images emerges as a promising strategy, merging high spatial resolution with comprehensive spectral data, particularly beneficial in agri-food applications, from lab experiments to field operations (Fu et al. 2020; Ilniyaz et al. 2023; Gkillas et al. 2023).",
    "This method represents a more accessible and less expensive alternative that drastically reduces the complexity of hyperspectral technology applications."
  ]
}